text: Most of the water must be locked in ice, but tidal heating could melt enough water for an underlying ocean of brine.
On Europa, the hydrogen could then combine with oxygen gas or other oxidants to power life.
Oxygen reaching the brine layer below could combine with electron donors from crustal vents and occur on Earth in rock strata several kilometers below the surface, where it may support lithotrophs.
However, an alternative source of chemical energy might be the influx of charged particles accelerated in Jupiter’s magnetic field.
Charged particles entering Europa’s ice can react with water to form hydrogen molecular oxygen.
These schemes are highly speculative— to take a closer look at Europa and its sister moons.
Photosynthesis is impossible at Jupiter’s distance from the Sun.
If such oceans do exist, how could they support life without photosynthesis?
